Recent evidence suggests that at least some insect species might plausibly
feel pain. These findings should prompt researchers to think about the welfare
implications of insect experiments.

Recent evidence suggests that at least some insect species might plausibly
feel pain. This Perspective argues that researchers need to rethink the
welfare implications of these findings for experiments that use insects.

